import java.util.*;
class Solution {
    public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {
        int i,j;
        for(i=0;i<nums.length;i++){
            for(j=i+1;j<nums.length;j++){
                if(i!=j){
                    if(target==nums[i]+nums[j]){
                        System.out.println(i+","+j);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    public static void main(String[] args){
        Scanner s=new Scanner(System.in);
        int n=s.nextInt();
        int[] a=new int[n];
        int i;
        for(i=0;i<n;i++){
            a[i]=s.nextInt();
        }
        int b=s.nextInt();

        twoSum(a, b);
    }
}


ChatGPT said:
Your Java program has the right idea for solving the Two Sum problem â€” finding two indices in an array whose elements add up to a target value. However, there are some critical issues in your code:

âŒ Problems in Your Code:
twoSum should return int[], but it doesn't return anything.

twoSum is a non-static method but is being called from a static context (main).

You are printing the indices instead of returning them.

You donâ€™t handle the case when no pair is found.

Brute-force logic is correct but not efficient.

âœ… Corrected Version:
java
Copy
Edit
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public static int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < nums.length; j++) {
                if (nums[i] + nums[j] == target) {
                    return new int[]{i, j}; // return as soon as found
                }
            }
        }
        return new int[]{}; // return empty array if not found
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner s = new Scanner(System.in);
        int n = s.nextInt();
        int[] a = new int[n];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            a[i] = s.nextInt();
        }
        int b = s.nextInt();

        int[] result = twoSum(a, b);
        if (result.length == 2) {
            System.out.println(result[0] + "," + result[1]);
        } else {
            System.out.println("No valid pair found.");
        }
    }
}
ğŸ”„ Optional Efficient Version Using HashMap (O(n) Time):
java
Copy
Edit
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public static int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {
        Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            int complement = target - nums[i];
            if(map.containsKey(complement)) {
                return new int[]{map.get(complement), i};
            }
            map.put(nums[i], i);
        }
        return new int[]{};
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner s = new Scanner(System.in);
        int n = s.nextInt();
        int[] a = new int[n];
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            a[i] = s.nextInt();
        }
        int b = s.nextInt();

        int[] result = twoSum(a, b);
        if(result.length == 2) {
            System.out.println(result[0] + "," + result[1]);
        } else {
            System.out.println("No valid pair found.");
        }
    }
}
