You said:
without size how can we give elements at run time in array in java


ChatGPT said:
In Java, arrays require a fixed size at the time of creation â€” you cannot change the size later. So if you donâ€™t know the number of elements at runtime, you should use an ArrayList instead.

âœ… Recommended: Use ArrayList (Dynamic Size)
java
Copy
Edit
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

        System.out.println("Enter numbers (type -1 to stop):");
        while (true) {
            int num = scanner.nextInt();
            if (num == -1) break;       // Sentinel value to stop input
            list.add(num);              // Dynamically add element
        }

        System.out.println("You entered: " + list);
    }
}
ğŸ” If You Must Use an Array (Not Recommended)
You can simulate dynamic input by:

Using an ArrayList to collect values.

Converting it to an array at the end.

java
Copy
Edit
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
// take input in loop...
Integer[] array = list.toArray(new Integer[0]);
ğŸ“Œ Why Not Arrays?
Arrays require size: int[] arr = new int[5]; â†’ fixed size.

ArrayList handles size and memory management for you.

