ChatGPT said:
Great question! You're asking how we can access elements in the arrays in the binary search solution without knowing the size ahead of time. Letâ€™s break it down step by step.

ğŸ” Step 1: We DO Know Array Sizes
In the code:

java
Copy
Edit
int m = nums1.length;
int n = nums2.length;
We get the sizes of the arrays at runtime using .length. So we donâ€™t hardcode sizes â€” instead, we use the length of the input arrays passed to the function.

ğŸ” Step 2: We Don't "Ask" the User for Size
If you're thinking of input like:

java
Copy
Edit
Scanner s = new Scanner(System.in);
int n = s.nextInt();  // â† This is where size is manually asked
In competitive programming or LeetCode-style code, the arrays are already passed as parameters, like:

java
Copy
Edit
public double findMedianSortedArrays(int[] nums1, int[] nums2)
So the array size is already known when the function starts â€” we donâ€™t manually ask or set it.

ğŸ§  What About Accessing Values?
We use indices to access array values:

java
Copy
Edit
nums1[partitionX - 1]
Here we access specific positions during binary search. But weâ€™re careful about out-of-bound errors:

java
Copy
Edit
int maxLeftX = (partitionX == 0) ? Integer.MIN_VALUE : nums1[partitionX - 1];
If partitionX == 0, we donâ€™t try to access nums1[-1], which would crash. Instead, we safely use:

java
Copy
Edit
Integer.MIN_VALUE
as a dummy "smallest possible number".

ğŸ“Œ Summary
Concept	How It's Handled
Array size	Use .length of array
Input from user	Not done here â€” arrays are passed directly
Accessing elements safely	Use conditions to avoid out-of-bounds
No hardcoded sizes used	Binary search handles varying sizes automatically

