You said:
what kind of numbers are there in java program like prime,armstrong,strong,happy just like that
 


ChatGPT said:
Great question! In Java (or any programming language), you can classify and work with special types of numbers based on mathematical properties. Hereâ€™s a list of interesting and commonly studied number types with short definitions:

ğŸ”¢ Popular Special Numbers in Java Programming
Number Type	Description	Example(s)
Prime Number	A number greater than 1 with only two divisors: 1 and itself	2, 3, 5, 7, 11
Composite Number	Has more than two factors (not 1 or prime)	4, 6, 8, 9
Palindrome Number	Reads the same forward and backward	121, 1331, 12321
Armstrong Number	Sum of its digits raised to the power of the number of digits = number	153 â†’ 1Â³+5Â³+3Â³
Perfect Number	Sum of its proper divisors equals the number	6 â†’ 1+2+3 = 6
Strong Number	Sum of factorials of digits equals the number	145 â†’ 1!+4!+5!
Happy Number	Repeated sum of squares of digits eventually reaches 1	19 â†’ 1Â²+9Â² = 82... eventually â†’ 1
Harshad Number	Divisible by the sum of its digits	18 â†’ 1+8 = 9 â†’ 18%9 == 0
Duck Number	Contains at least one zero, but not starting with zero	102, 1204
Spy Number	Sum of digits = product of digits	123 â†’ 1+2+3=6, 1Ã—2Ã—3=6
Automorphic Number	Square ends with the number itself	25Â² = 625, ends with 25
Neon Number	Sum of digits of square equals the number	9Â² = 81 â†’ 8+1 = 9
Buzz Number	Ends with 7 or divisible by 7	27, 49
Even/Odd Number	Even â†’ divisible by 2, Odd â†’ not divisible by 2	2, 4, 6 (even); 1, 3 (odd)

âœ… Examples in Java
Hereâ€™s a quick example of checking an Armstrong number:

java
Copy
Edit
public class Armstrong {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int num = 153, sum = 0, temp = num;

        while (temp > 0) {
            int digit = temp % 10;
            sum += Math.pow(digit, 3);  // 3 is number of digits
            temp /= 10;
        }

        if (sum == num)
            System.out.println(num + " is an Armstrong number.");
        else
            System.out.println(num + " is not an Armstrong number.");
    }
}
ğŸ“˜ Want to Practice?
You can try writing small Java programs for each of these types. Let me know which type you'd like next â€” I can give you code and explanation!

