Hereâ€™s a detailed explanation of Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) in Java, covering concepts, why we use them, and realistic examples for each. This will help you understand not just how to use OOP in Java, but also why these concepts matter.

ğŸš€ What is OOP in Java?
Java is an object-oriented language, which means everything in Java revolves around objects â€” entities that combine data (fields) and behavior (methods). OOP helps you:

Organize code better.

Reuse and extend existing code easily.

Improve security and scalability in applications.

ğŸ”‘ 1. Class and Object
A class is a template or blueprint. An object is an instance of a class.

ğŸ”¹ Example:
java
Copy
Edit
class Car {
    String color = "Red";

    void drive() {
        System.out.println("The car is driving");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car myCar = new Car(); // Creating an object
        System.out.println(myCar.color);
        myCar.drive();
    }
}
âœ… Why use it?: To structure your code around real-world entities like cars, students, accounts, etc.

ğŸ” 2. Encapsulation
Encapsulation = data hiding. Keep variables private and access them through getters/setters.

ğŸ”¹ Example:
java
Copy
Edit
class Account {
    private int balance;

    public void setBalance(int b) {
        if (b > 0) balance = b;
    }

    public int getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
}
âœ… Why use it?: To protect internal data from external tampering and keep control over access/modification.

ğŸ§¬ 3. Inheritance
Allows one class to inherit from another. Promotes code reuse.

ğŸ”¹ Example:
java
Copy
Edit
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Animal is eating");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Dog is barking");
    }
}
âœ… Why use it?: To create a parent-child relationship and avoid repeating code.

ğŸ§  4. Polymorphism
Polymorphism = one name, many forms

a) Method Overloading (Compile-time)
java
Copy
Edit
class Calculator {
    int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
    int add(int a, int b, int c) { return a + b + c; }
}
b) Method Overriding (Runtime)
java
Copy
Edit
class Animal {
    void sound() { System.out.println("Some sound"); }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    void sound() { System.out.println("Meow"); }
}
âœ… Why use it?: To allow different behavior with the same method name depending on context.

ğŸ§± 5. Abstraction
Abstraction hides unnecessary details and only shows whatâ€™s essential.

a) Using abstract class
java
Copy
Edit
