âœ… Internally, StringBuilder.reverse() reverses the character sequence.

âœ… 2. Using Collections.reverse() for character list
If you have a list of characters (not an array), you can do:

java
Copy
Edit
List<Character> list = new ArrayList<>();
for (char c : "hello".toCharArray()) {
    list.add(c);
}

Collections.reverse(list);
for (char c : list) {
    System.out.print(c); // Output: olleh
}
âŒ No method like Arrays.reverse() exists
You cannot directly reverse a primitive array (like char[]) using Arrays class â€” you'll have to write a manual loop (like the two-pointer swap method I gave earlier).

ğŸ§  Summary:
Structure	Built-in Reverse Method	Notes
String	new StringBuilder(str).reverse()	Best for simple use
List<Character>	Collections.reverse(list)	Works only on List
char[]	âŒ No direct method	Use a manual loop

