You said:
Write a program to compress a string by replacing consecutive repeated characters with the character followed by its count (e.g., "aabcc" â†’ "a2b1c2"). If the compressed string length is greater than the original string length, return the original string instead. If the compressed string length is equal to the original string length , return the compressed string


ChatGPT said:
Here's a Java program that compresses a string by replacing consecutive repeated characters with the character followed by its count.

It also checks:

If the compressed string is shorter, return it.

If the compressed string is equal in length, return it.

If the compressed string is longer, return the original string.

âœ… Java Code:
java
Copy
Edit
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Main {
    public static String compressString(String str) {
        StringBuilder compressed = new StringBuilder();
        int count = 1;

        // Loop through the string
        for (int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {
            // Count consecutive characters
            while (i + 1 < str.length() && str.charAt(i) == str.charAt(i + 1)) {
                count++;
                i++;
            }

            // Append character and its count
            compressed.append(str.charAt(i)).append(count);
            count = 1;
        }

        // Compare lengths
        if (compressed.length() > str.length()) {
            return str;
        } else {
            return compressed.toString();
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        String input = sc.nextLine();
        String result = compressString(input);
        System.out.println(result);
        sc.close();
    }
}
ğŸ§ª Example:
