You said:
multipath inheritence


ChatGPT said:
ğŸŒ Multiple Path Inheritance (Diamond Problem) in Java
Java does not support multiple inheritance with classes directly to avoid ambiguity known as the Diamond Problem, but it allows multiple inheritance with interfaces.

ğŸ”¶ What is Multi-Path Inheritance?
Multi-path inheritance happens when a class inherits from two classes that share a common parent.
This creates ambiguity if both parent classes have the same method.

ğŸš« Java doesn't allow this with classes:
java
Copy
Edit
class A {
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Class A");
    }
}

class B extends A {
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Class B");
    }
}

class C extends A {
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Class C");
    }
}

// âŒ Invalid in Java
// class D extends B, C {
//     public static void main(String[] args) {
//         D obj = new D();
//         obj.display(); // Ambiguity! Which display()? B or C?
//     }
// }
âœ… Javaâ€™s Solution: Use Interfaces
java
Copy
Edit
interface A {
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("Interface A");
    }
}

interface B extends A {
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("Interface B");
    }
}

interface C extends A {
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("Interface C");
    }
}

class D implements B, C {
    public void show() {
        // Resolving ambiguity manually
        B.super.show();
        C.super.show();
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        D obj = new D();
        obj.show();
    }
}
âœ… Output:
graphql
Copy
Edit
Interface B
Interface C
ğŸ” Summary:
Feature	With Classes	With Interfaces
Multiple Inheritance	âŒ Not allowed	âœ… Allowed
Diamond Problem Risk	âœ… Yes	âœ… Avoided with default and manual override
Java Approach	Use Interfaces	Use super with interface name

Let me know if you'd like this in PDF format or explained with a diagram.






