ChatGPT said:
Your Java code has multiple issues â€” both syntax and structural. Below is the corrected and complete version of the program that uses interface-based loose coupling with LaserPrinter and InkjetPrinter, plus a PrintManager to control printing.

âœ… Corrected Java Program
java
Copy
Edit
import java.util.Scanner;

// Printer Interface
interface Printer {
    void print(String content);
}

// Laser Printer Implementation
class LaserPrinter implements Printer {
    public void print(String content) {
        System.out.println("Laser Printer Output: " + content);
    }
}

// Inkjet Printer Implementation
class InkjetPrinter implements Printer {
    public void print(String content) {
        System.out.println("Inkjet Printer Output: " + content);
    }
}

// Print Manager using Loose Coupling
class PrintManager {
    private Printer printer;

    public PrintManager(Printer printer) {
        this.printer = printer;
    }

    public void printDocument(String content) {
        printer.print(content);
    }
}

// Main class
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        // Input document
        System.out.print("Enter a document: ");
        String doc = sc.nextLine();

        // Choose printer
        System.out.println("Choose printer (1. Laser, 2. Inkjet): ");
        int choice = sc.nextInt();

        // Choose implementation
        Printer printer;
        if (choice == 1) {
            printer = new LaserPrinter();
        } else {
            printer = new InkjetPrinter();
        }

        // Use print manager
        PrintManager manager = new PrintManager(printer);
        manager.printDocument(doc);

        sc.close();
    }
}
ğŸ’¡ Highlights:
âœ… Loose coupling using the Printer interface.

âœ… Different printer types (LaserPrinter, InkjetPrinter) can be swapped.

âœ… PrintManager is unaware of which concrete printer is used.

If you'd like this refactored for Spring or GUI-based printing, let me know!
